<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Unix on KevCaz's Website</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/unix/</link><description>Recent content in Unix on KevCaz's Website</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>Content under CC0 1.0 Universal unless otherwise specified.</copyright><lastBuildDate>Mon, 29 Oct 2018 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/unix/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Modify and combine a set of files in one</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-29_modify_and_combine/</link><pubDate>Mon, 29 Oct 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-29_modify_and_combine/</guid><description>&lt;p>Today I was looking for a way to combine a set of files in one but before
appending a given file, the 2 first lines as well as the last line had to be removed. On Stackoverflow &lt;i class="fa fa-stack-overflow" aria-hidden="true">&lt;/i> I found a couple of answers (see questions &lt;a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18006581/how-to-append-contents-of-multiple-files-into-one-file">18006581&lt;/a>, &lt;a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12176492/shell-delete-the-last-line-of-a-huge-text-log-file">12176492&lt;/a> and &lt;a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5410757/delete-lines-in-a-text-file-that-contain-a-specific-string">5410757&lt;/a>) and based on these I decided to use a combination of
&lt;a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/head-invocation.html">head&lt;/a> and &lt;a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/tail-invocation.html">tail&lt;/a>. I ended up creating the following shell script:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">3
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">4
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">5
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">6
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">7
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#9893a5">#!/bin/bash
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#9893a5">&lt;/span>touch biblio.yaml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#286983">for&lt;/span> f in refs/*.yml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#286983">do&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span> tail -n+3 &lt;span style="color:#d7827e">$f&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#797593">|&lt;/span> head -n-1 &amp;gt;&amp;gt; biblio.yaml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span> &lt;span style="color:#d7827e">echo&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#ea9d34">&amp;#34;\n&amp;#34;&lt;/span> &amp;gt;&amp;gt; biblio.yaml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#286983">done&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Let&amp;rsquo;s break it down:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>From one character encoding to another</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-16_from_one_character/</link><pubDate>Tue, 16 Oct 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-16_from_one_character/</guid><description>&lt;p>Today I needed to check the character encoding of a file, I found &lt;a href="https://www.tecmint.com/convert-files-to-utf-8-encoding-in-linux/">this page that explains how to do this&lt;/a>. Basically the command &lt;code>file&lt;/code> will give you the info, for instance:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">2
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>$ file example.md
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>example.md: ASCII text
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>options &lt;code>-i&lt;/code> for &lt;code>--mime&lt;/code> and &lt;code>-b&lt;/code> for &lt;code>--brief&lt;/code> will give:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">2
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>$ file -bi example.md
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>text/plain&lt;span style="color:#797593">;&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#d7827e">charset&lt;/span>&lt;span style="color:#797593">=&lt;/span>us-ascii
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>I figured out that I needed to convert my file from one character encoding to another and so I used &lt;code>iconv&lt;/code>. As mentioned in the link above,
&lt;code>iconv -l&lt;/code> will give you the list of character encodings &lt;code>iconv&lt;/code> handles. In my case, I needed to convert the file from &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO/IEC_8859-1">Latin1, aka iso8859-1&lt;/a>
to &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UTF-8">UTF-8&lt;/a>, so I used the following command line:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Unzip more than one file</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/09/2018-09-25_unzip_more_than/</link><pubDate>Tue, 25 Sep 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/09/2018-09-25_unzip_more_than/</guid><description>&lt;p>Few days ago, I was trying to unzip a set of files and it did
not work, so I looked up on the internet and found this very detailed &lt;a href="https://chrisjean.com/unzip-multiple-files-from-linux-command-line/">post by Chris Jean&lt;/a> that explains why&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>unzip path/*.zip
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>gives you an error whereas&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>unzip &lt;span style="color:#ea9d34">&amp;#39;path/*.zip&amp;#39;&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>works like a charm!&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Thanks Chris!&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>How to count non-blank lines of a set of files?</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/09/2018-09-23_how_to_count/</link><pubDate>Sun, 23 Sep 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/09/2018-09-23_how_to_count/</guid><description>&lt;p>Yesterday, I was trying to find a way to count lines of a set of R files without comments nor empty lines and found &lt;a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/114814/count-non-blank-lines-of-code-in-bash">this answer on stackoverflow&lt;/a>:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>cat R/* &lt;span style="color:#797593">|&lt;/span> sed &lt;span style="color:#ea9d34">&amp;#39;/^\s*#/d;/^\s*$/d&amp;#39;&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#797593">|&lt;/span> wc -l
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Exactly what I needed! A few explanations are in order:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cat_(Unix)">cat&lt;/a> reads files sequentially;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pipeline_(Unix)">&amp;quot;|&amp;quot;&lt;/a> is the the pipe operator;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sed">sed&lt;/a> parses and transforms text;&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wc_(Unix)">wc&lt;/a> counts words, lines and more!&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>Basically, counting lines of a file is done with the option &lt;code>-l&lt;/code> of &lt;code>wc&lt;/code>
(option &lt;code>-m&lt;/code> for characters, see &lt;code>man wc&lt;/code> to learn more):&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>